              "lessonLabel": "Lesson 1",
              "title": "25m Canadian History: Grades 5-6 - Lesson 1",
              "body": "Joe and the Wreck of the Tribune\n⍞ Materials: Joe and the Wreck of the Tribune, Canadian atlas or map of Nova Scotia\n\n➜ INTRO\nThe years 1800-1900 were a momentous century for the history of Canada. It saw wars, rebellions, large waves of immigration, new and expanded settlements, exploration to the west and north, and Canada's Confederation of 1867, with more provinces and territories joining in the decades that followed. This course uses the narrative history The Story of Canada to provide an overview of the major events of the years 1800-1900, and a historical novel, a picture book, and a graphic novel to immerse students in three distinct moments in time: life in a fishing village on Nova Scotia's Chebucto Peninsula at the turn of the century, the life of Tecumseh, a Shawnee chief and British army ally in the War of 1812, and the Confederation Conferences of 1864, where the wheels of Canada's Confederacy were set in motion.\nThe first book, Joe and the Wreck of the Tribune, tells the story of a thirteen-year old boy who risked his life to save drowning sailors from the wreck of the H.M.S. Tribune, off the coast of Nova Scotia. This historical fiction novel imagines a backstory for the boy only known to history as \"Joe Cracker,\" and it paints a detailed picture of what life was like in a small fishing village around 1800.\n\n➜ READ, NARRATE, & DISCUSS\np.1-13 \"Wisps of fog\" - \"all about the ocean.\"\n• Who are the characters you meet as the novel opens? How are they related to each other? What are they like?\nYou may choose to keep a character list with some notes.\n\n➜ MAP WORK\n⍞ Map Resources: Canadian Student Atlas p. or any other map (including online) showing Nova Scotia. \nLocate Halifax and the Chebucto Peninsula. Does your map show Herring Cove?\n\n➜ VIEW\n∞ Video Link: Explore Herring Cove\nWatch a video tour of Herring Cove with Senator Stan Kutcher. If you're short on time, feel free to skip 1:58-2:54. This whole video could be saved for another point in the course, but it touches on many themes of the novel, so it's definitely not a video to miss!",
              "teacherNotes": "★ TEACHER NOTE\nPlease read the header pages for this course which lists the page numbers for the sensitive content you may wish to preview.",
              "editUrl": "https://airtable.com/apphTWdjAdJEcAmoe/pago27hsdn3q8TtGK?XRKkD=recyw9Tjk8xQIKR3q&6J82c=recuzuy7l87ySP4mm"
            },
            {
              "termNumber": 1,
              "termLabel": "Term 1",
              "weekNumber": 2,
              "weekLabel": "Week 2",
              "sequence": 2,
              "lessonLabel": "Lesson 2",
              "title": "25m Canadian History: Grades 5-6 - Lesson 2",
              "body": "Joe and the Wreck of the Tribune\n⍞ Materials: Joe and the Wreck of the Tribune\n\n➜ RECAP\nWhat do you recall from the opening chapters of the novel?\n\n➜ READ, NARRATE, & DISCUSS\np.13 \"I broke my arm\" - \"Next job, Eli's shed.\"\n• As you read, compare Joe's daily life to yours. For example, have you or anyone in your family ever broken a bone? How was it treated? How was Joe's treatment different? Or, what are your chores in the morning? Are they similar or different to Joe's?",
              "teacherNotes": "",
              "editUrl": "https://airtable.com/apphTWdjAdJEcAmoe/pago27hsdn3q8TtGK?XRKkD=recyw9Tjk8xQIKR3q&6J82c=rec046wlJNsqSX4Or"
            },
